definition.value: Any steroid lactone that is a C28 steroid with a modified side chain forming a lactone ring and its substituted derivatives.
A dipeptide formed from L-phenylalanine and L-isoleucine residues.
A hydrochloride resulting from the reaction of equimolar amounts of 3,6-diaminoacridine and hydrogen chloride.
A dipeptide formed from L-phenylalanine and L-methionine residues.
A guanosine 5'-phosphate that is the N(7)-methyl derivative of guanosine 5'-monophosphate.
A nucleotide residue derived from N(2)-methylguanosine 5'-monophosphate
A purine ribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate that is GMP bearing an N(2)-methyl substituent.
A hydrochloride resulting from the reaction of 3,6-diaminoacridine with 2 mol eq. of hydrogen chloride.
A nucleotide residue derived from 5-methylcytidine 5'-monophosphate.
A pyrimidine ribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate having 5-methylcytosine as the nucleobase.
A hydrochloride resulting from the reaction of equimolar amounts of 3,6-diamino-10-methylacridinium chloride and hydrogen chloride.
A mixture of 3,6-diaminoacridine dihydrochloride and 3,6-diamino-10-methylacridinium chloride hydrochloride.
A mixture comprising 3,6-diamino-10-methylacridinium chloride (usually 60-70%) and 3,6-diaminoacridine monohydrochloride (usually 40-30%).
A nucleotide residue derived from N(3)-methylpseudouridine 5'-monophosphate.
A C-nucleoside phosphate that is pseudouridine 5'-monophosphate, bearing an additional N(3)-methyl substituent.
A pyrimidone that is uracil with a methyl group at position 3.
A pyrimidone that is uracil with a methyl group at position 6.
A nucleotide residue derived from N(1)-methyladenosine 5'-monophosphate.
A purine ribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate that is AMP monomethylated on N(1).
A member of the class of pyrazoles that is N-methylpyrazole substituted by a carboxy group substituents at position 5.
A member of the class of pyrazoles that is  N-methylpyrazole substituted by a carboxy group at position 3.
A memebr of the class of pyrazoles that is 1H-pyrazole with methyl and carboxylic acid group substituents at positions 5 and 3 respectively.
A memebr of the class of pyrazoles that is 1H-pyrazole with methyl and carboxylic acid group substituents at positions 4 and 3 respectively.
A member of the class of pyrazoles that is N-methylpyrazole substituted by a carboxy group at position 4.
A member of the class of pyrazoles that is 1H-pyrazole with methyl and carboxylic acid group substituents at positions 3 and 4 respectively.
An imidazolyl carboxylic acid that is 1H-imidazole with methyl and carboxylic acid group substituents at positions 1 and 2 respectively.

An  imidazolyl carboxylic acid that is 1H-imidazole with methyl and carboxylic acid group substituents at positions 5 and 2 respectively.
An imidazolyl carboxylic acid that is 1H-imidazole with methyl and carboxylic acid group substituents at positions 5 and 4 respectively.
A nucleotide residue derived from 2'-O-methylcytidine 5'-monophosphate.

A single-stranded DNA oligonucleotide containing four consecutive thymidyl residues, T1, T2, T3 and T4, arranged in the direction from the 5'-terminus to the 3'-terminus, with a (6-4) lesion at the central T2 and T3 residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-phenylalanine and L-proline residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-phenylalanine and L-tryptophan residues.
A phosphorus oxoanion obtained by selective deprotonation of two of the three phosphate OH groups of thiophosphoric acid.
A dipeptide formed from L-proline and L-alanine residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-proline and L-asparagine residues.
A quaternary ammonium ion resulting from the protonation of the amino group of aclacinomycin T. The major species at pH 7.3.
A dipeptide formed from L-proline and L-aspartic acid residues.
A dipeptide formed from L-proline and L-glutamine residues.
A hydrochloride resulting from the reaction of aclacinomycin T with an equimolar amount of hydrogen chloride.
An aralkylamino compound that is histamine bearing a methyl substituent at the alpha-position.

A methoxynaphthalene that is 2-methoxynaphthalene substituted by a carboxy ethyl group at position 6. Naproxen is a non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drug commonly used for the reduction of pain, fever, inflammation  and stiffness caused by conditions such as osteoarthritis, kidney stones, rheumatoid arthritis, psoriatic arthritis, gout, ankylosing spondylitis, menstrual cramps, tendinitis, bursitis, and for the treatment of primary dysmenorrhea. It works by inhibiting both the COX-1 and COX-2 enzymes.
An aralkylamino compound that is histamine bearing a methyl substituent at the 5 position on the ring.
An aralkylamino compound that is histamine bearing a methyl substituent at the 2 position on the ring.
A dipeptide formed from L-proline and L-glutamic acid residues.
A pyrimidone that is uracil with methyl group substituents at positions 1 and 3.
A polyanionic polymer obtained by global deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of Cys-tRNA(Sec).
A pyrimidone that is uracil with methyl group substituents at positions 1 and 5.
